<h2>Date Picker — the first temporal preset</h2>
<p>The <strong>date-picker</strong> is the first named shallow <em>preset</em> over the abstract <a href="/blocks/temporal/">temporal</a> core: a single calendar-date picker. It is the core with two dimensions pinned — <a href="/intents/temporal/">Temporal Intent</a> <code>presentation=media</code> (a spatial calendar grid) and <code>granularity=point</code> (one date) — bound to the native <code>&lt;input type="date"&gt;</code> anchor. It adds <strong>no machinery the core lacks</strong>; it inherits locale-aware parse/format, keyboard roving, and the native form-control baseline for free.</p>

<blockquote>
  <p><strong>A preset is a dimension pin, not new machinery (#713 option C).</strong> date-picker = <a href="/blocks/temporal/">temporal</a> with <code>presentation=media</code> + <code>granularity=point</code> pinned and the <code>input[type=date]</code> anchor bound. The calendar/locale/keyboard logic is the core's; this block only chooses the paradigm and the anchor — the family rule (one core, members are pins), like the <a href="/blocks/droplist/">droplist</a> members.</p>
</blockquote>

<h3>Native-first — the date input is the anchor and fallback</h3>
<we-data-table>
<table class="data-table">
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Feature</th><th>Disposition</th><th>Tier</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Single date value, keyboard entry, form-assoc, validity</td><td><code>built-in</code> — native <code>&lt;input type="date"&gt;</code></td><td>1</td><td>Zero-JS baseline; the no-JS and keyboard fallback.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Spatial calendar grid (media presentation)</td><td><code>built-in</code> — the core's <code>media</code> surface</td><td>2</td><td>Pointer/spatial selection layered over the native input.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Locale-aware parse / display</td><td><code>compose</code> — <a href="/intents/locale/">Locale Intent</a> (via the core)</td><td>1</td><td>Inherited; the date-picker pins nothing here.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Grid roving (arrow keys across weeks)</td><td><code>compose</code> — <a href="/intents/focus-delegation/">Focus Delegation</a> (via the core)</td><td>2</td><td>Inherited from the core's media surface.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Time / range / multi</td><td><code>compose</code> — sibling presets</td><td>3</td><td>Out of scope: time-picker, datetime-picker, date-range-picker are the other pins over the same core.</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
</we-data-table>

<h3>Altitude 1 — the pin over the native anchor</h3>
{% highlight "html" %}
<!-- date-picker = temporal pinned to media + point, over input[type=date] -->
<label for="start">Start date</label>
<input id="start" type="date" name="start"
       temporal="presentation=media;granularity=point"
       anchor="start-grid">
<div id="start-grid" role="grid" aria-label="Choose a date" popover>
  <!-- calendar cells from the core's media surface; the native input stays the fallback -->
</div>
{% endhighlight %}

<h3>Boundaries</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>No machinery of its own.</strong> Everything — the grid, locale formatting, roving — is the <a href="/blocks/temporal/">temporal</a> core's. This block is the <code>media</code> + <code>point</code> pin and the <code>input[type=date]</code> binding, nothing more.</li>
  <li><strong>Native is the baseline.</strong> The real <code>&lt;input type="date"&gt;</code> stays form-associated and keyboard-accessible; the calendar grid is the enhancement, not a replacement.</li>
  <li><strong>One member of a family.</strong> time-picker (<code>input[type=time]</code>), datetime-picker (<code>[type=datetime-local]</code>), and date-range-picker (<code>granularity=range</code>) are the sibling pins over the same core.</li>
</ul>
